## Summary Report: Transformers.js Pipeline Base Class and Multimodal Patterns

Based on my thorough analysis of the Transformers.js codebase, here's the complete understanding of the pipeline architecture:

---

### 1. **Pipeline Base Class** (`/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775400101424-qf9gwy/src/pipelines.js`, lines 164-185)

**Constructor & Properties:**
```javascript
export class Pipeline extends Callable {
    /**
     * Create a new Pipeline.
     * @param {Object} options An object containing the following properties:
     * @param {string} [options.task] The task of the pipeline. Useful for specifying subtasks.
     * @param {PreTrainedModel} [options.model] The model used by the pipeline.
     * @param {PreTrainedTokenizer} [options.tokenizer=null] The tokenizer used by the pipeline (if any).
     * @param {Processor} [options.processor=null] The processor used by the pipeline (if any).
     */
    constructor({ task, model, tokenizer = null, processor = null }) {
        super();
        this.task = task;
        this.model = model;
        this.tokenizer = tokenizer;
        this.processor = processor;
    }

    /** @type {DisposeType} */
    async dispose() {
        await this.model.dispose();
    }
}
```

**Key Points:**
- All pipelines extend the `Pipeline` class and inherit from `Callable`
- The base class stores `task`, `model`, `tokenizer`, and `processor` as instance properties
- Provides a `dispose()` method for cleanup (currently only disposes the model)
- Processors are optional and stored as `this.processor`

---

### 2. **RawImage Image Loading Utility** (`/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775400101424-qf9gwy/src/utils/image.js`, lines 77-133)

**Class Definition (lines 77-91):**
```javascript
export class RawImage {
    /**
     * Create a new `RawImage` object.
     * @param {Uint8ClampedArray|Uint8Array} data The pixel data.
     * @param {number} width The width of the image.
     * @param {number} height The height of the image.
     * @param {1|2|3|4} channels The number of channels.
     */
    constructor(data, width, height, channels) {
        this.data = data;
        this.width = width;
        this.height = height;
        this.channels = channels;
    }

    /**
     * Returns the size of the image (width, height).
     * @returns {[number, number]} The size of the image (width, height).
     */
    get size() {
        return [this.width, this.height];
    }
```

**Static Read Method (lines 117-133):**
```javascript
static async read(input) {
    if (input instanceof RawImage) {
        return input;
    } else if (typeof input === 'string' || input instanceof URL) {
        return await this.fromURL(input);
    } else if (input instanceof Blob) {
        return await this.fromBlob(input);
    } else if (
        (typeof HTMLCanvasElement !== "undefined" && input instanceof HTMLCanvasElement)
        ||
        (typeof OffscreenCanvas !== "undefined" && input instanceof OffscreenCanvas)
    ) {
        return this.fromCanvas(input);
    } else {
        throw new Error(`Unsupported input type: ${typeof input}`);
    }
}
```

**Helper Function in Pipelines (lines 91-98):**
```javascript
async function prepareImages(images) {
    if (!Array.isArray(images)) {
        images = [images];
    }

    // Possibly convert any non-images to images
    return await Promise.all(images.map(x => RawImage.read(x)));
}
```

**Key Points:**
- `RawImage` stores pixel data, width, height, and channel count
- Supports multiple input types: RawImage, string URLs, Blobs, HTMLCanvasElement, OffscreenCanvas
- `prepareImages()` is used in all image pipelines to normalize inputs to `RawImage[]`

